   {:e #blake3 "5053768c6bc06b11bfd25bd62d797f2d75557daaf203bd6823e9a57cac2bcf15" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Policy Completeness Principle; Session entity: :task/t-9df08f11; Session entity: :task/t-03cc1d52; Session entity: :recon/trace-b6e4f8f179754085\nADR-FOUNDATION-031 PROPOSAL: Policy Completeness Principle — every behavioral constant is an implicit policy decision. Hard-coded constants that govern system behavior violate C8 (substrate independence) because they encode domain assumptions in the kernel. The BoundaryRegistry weights are the existence proof: they are already datoms, already calibrated through the hypothesis ledger, already CRDT-mergeable. This pattern should generalize. THREE CATEGORIES: (1) Behavioral thresholds (~15-20 constants): harvest confidence floor, crystallization threshold, task reconciliation threshold, harvest urgency threshold, alert fatigue suppression, connection hub degree, budget limits. These SHOULD be policy datoms — different domains need different thresholds. (2) Structural parameters (~10-15 constants): MIN_KEYWORD_LEN, max concepts displayed, innate fade threshold, budget section limits. These are UI/UX concerns, not domain policy. MAYBE datoms, lower priority. (3) Algorithmic weights (~10 constants): routing coefficients, evidence signal weights, surprise alpha. These SHOULD be datoms — they are the calibratable parameters of the learning system. SCOPE: A full audit of all constants across the codebase, classification into categories, and a phased migration plan. Phase 1: audit and classify (~2 hours). Phase 2: wire Category 1 + 3 to policy datoms (~1-2 sessions). Phase 3: wire calibration feedback for Category 3 (~1 session). This is NOT urgent — the system works with constants. But it's the difference between a tool that you configure and a system that learns its own configuration." :op :assert}
